article.description: Charde Houston scored 17 points to lead No. 11 Connecticut to a 57-44 victory over Rutgers (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) on Thursday night, the Scarlet Knights' lowest-scoring game of the season.
article.headline: Scarlet Knights held to lowest-scoring game
article.linkText: UConn posts 12th straight win vs. Rutgers
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Connecticut guard Ashley Valley has
waited four years for a game like this.

A little used reserve before this season, Valley was used to
playing behind stars Diana Taurasi and Sue Bird. Against Rutgers on
Thursday night, it was finally the senior guard's turn to shine.

Valley hit three 3-pointers and scored a career-high 12 points --
all in the first half -- to get No. 11 UConn (14-5, 7-1 Big East)
off to a fast start in a 57-44 win over seventh-ranked Rutgers, the
Scarlet Knights' lowest-scoring game of the season. Valley, in her
11th start this season, also had a career-high six rebounds and
never wilted under the Scarlet Knights' pressing defense.

"They're a very fast team and we just had to keep our
composure," Valley said.

Charde Houston led the Huskies with 17 points in their 12th
straight victory over Rutgers (15-5, 6-2). Rutgers has been on a
roll this season, knocking off powerhouses LSU, Tennessee and
Texas, but against their Big East nemesis, the Scarlet Knights came
up empty once more to drop to 0-11 on UConn home courts. Rutgers
was without senior guard Chelsea Newton, who suffered a concussion
Sunday in a 70-49 win over West Virginia and had been averaging
nine points a game.

Rutgers' coach C. Vivian Stringer said the absence of Newton had
an impact and she acknowledged the emergence of Valley, too.
Rutgers was more concerned about guarding Ann Strother, UConn's
main perimeter threat. Strother was held to four points, eight
below her average.

"We went on Ann Strother so we addressed that and Ashley
Valley, the no-name showed up, so to speak," Stringer said.

The Huskies never trailed and led by as many as 18. They
dominated inside, outscoring Rutgers 22-14 in the paint and
finished with a 45-35 rebounding edge. UConn's physical play
repeatedly landed the Huskies on the free-throw line, where they
hit 20 of 28 shots. Houston made the most of her trips to the
stripe, going 7-of-8.

Strother did manage to crack the 1,000 career-point barrier,
becoming the third UConn player this season to do so.

"It's a tribute to everybody really," Strother said.
"Everybody that was getting me the ball, screening for me and
doing everything for me."

Matee Ajavon led the Scarlet Knights with 20 points, and Cappie
Pondexter added 10 points and eight rebounds.

Ashley Battle had 10 points off the bench for UConn. She and
Houston led the Huskies with eight rebounds each.

After the Huskies raced out to 12-0 lead in the first 5 minutes,
the Scarlet Knights applied their trademark pressure defense and
got results -- sort of. UConn committed nine turnovers in the next 6
minutes but Rutgers failed to capitalize and scored just two points
off the miscues.

Rutgers missed its first eight shots of the period and got most
of the offense in the half from Ajavon, who had a dozen points on
4-of-11 shooting. Valley's third 3-pointer with 6 seconds left gave
the Huskies a 26-18 lead at the break.

"That was pretty big," UConn Coach Geno Auriemma said. "That
was a great shot of momentum for us going into the locker room."

The Huskies were coming off a 65-59 home loss to Notre Dame, a
performance that drew the blunt assessment from Auriemma that the
UConn guards were not very good. And the Scarlet Knights' defensive
reputation was drilled into them. Rutgers had just forced a Big
East season-high 29 turnovers against West Virginia.

Valley said she and her teammates had something to prove.

"That's all we've been hearing for the last two days is,
`(UConn) doesn't have any guards, Rutgers is too quick," Valley
said. "We're working hard and we're trying to do what we need to
and we did it tonight."
